{"ide-job-1": {"task": "The beeping noise for alarms that go off will not end even when closed and is driving me crazy", "status": "done", "mode": "autopilot", "auto_approve": false, "files_touched": [], "created": 1773664364.9220445, "agent_name": "code", "custom_name": null, "messages": [{"role": "user", "text": "The beeping noise for alarms that go off will not end even when closed and is driving me crazy", "ts": 1773664364.9220448}, {"role": "assistant", "text": "Here's what I found after digging through the alarm system:\n\n**The beeping is client-side** \u2014 generated by `playAlertBeep()` in bmo.js using Web Audio API oscillators every 2 seconds via `setInterval`. When you dismiss, `stopAlertLoop()` clears that interval on **that browser tab only**.\n\n**The likely culprit: your kiosk is also running** (`bmo-kiosk` is active). It's a separate Chromium instance that also receives the `alarm_fired` socket event and starts its own beeping loop. Dismissing on your phone doesn't stop the kiosk's beeping, and vice versa \u2014 there's no server-side \"alarm dismissed\" broadcast to sync all clients.\n\n**The fix** would be two things:\n1. **Add a server-side `alarm_dismissed` socket event** \u2014 when any client dismisses an alarm, the server broadcasts it to ALL clients so they all stop beeping.\n2. **Track dismissed alarm IDs on the client** \u2014 so if a dismissed alarm's socket event arrives late (race condition), it gets ignored.\n\nWant me to implement this fix? It would involve:\n- Adding a `/api/alarms/<id>/dismiss` endpoint in `app.py` that emits an `alarm_dismissed` socket event to all clients\n- Adding a `socket.on('alarm_dismissed')` handler in `bmo.js` that calls `stopAlertLoop()` and clears `alertFired`\n- Having `dismissAlert()` call that endpoint instead of just clearing local state", "ts": 1773664659.7895567}, {"role": "assistant", "text": "Error: cannot access local variable 'all_responses' where it is not associated with a value", "ts": 1773664659.7898443}, {"role": "user", "text": "You failed with: cannot access local variable 'all_responses' where it is not associated with a value", "ts": 1773667316.314904}, {"role": "assistant", "text": "The second occurrence (follow-up handler) looks fine \u2014 it uses `all_responses` only inside the autopilot branch and the `done` path just says \"Follow-up complete\" without referencing it. Now let me restart BMO:\n\nBMO needs your permission: This command could modify or delete data. Please confirm.\nCommand: sudo systemctl restart bmo\nSay 'yes' to confirm or 'no' to cancel.", "ts": 1773667339.7499566}, {"role": "user", "text": "I realized the noise goes off even if I is a good morning alarm that BMO already speaks out loud as well as the alarm goes off on all devices and does not stop on all once closed or snoozed on one you have to close or snooze on each which should be completely in sync with all devices", "ts": 1773667557.254485}, {"role": "assistant", "text": "Good \u2014 the `tag` field is already included in all `alarm_fired` emissions (`wake-up`, `timer`, and `reminder`). The client-side check `data.tag === 'wake-up'` will work correctly.\n\nNow let me restart BMO:\n\nBMO needs your permission: This command could modify or delete data. Please confirm.\nCommand: sudo systemctl restart bmo\nSay 'yes' to confirm or 'no' to cancel.", "ts": 1773667742.1736991}], "activity_log": [{"type": "status", "content": "Using code agent (mode: normal)", "ts": 1773664364.923784}, {"type": "thinking", "content": "\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f Normal mode \u2014 executing with confirmation...", "ts": 1773664364.9238293}, {"type": "log", "content": "[orchestrator] Agent override: code", "ts": 1773664364.9240181}, {"type": "log", "content": "[code_agent] Using Claude native tools (model=claude-opus-4.6)", "ts": 1773664364.9250872}, {"type": "log", "content": "[claude_tools] iter=1 stop=tool_use tools=[grep_files, grep_files, grep_files]", "ts": 1773664370.3219707}, {"type": "log", "co